How many hours does the train travel?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: One of the main purposes of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) in the United States is to collect information about traffic fatalities. NHTSA's Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS) uses data from all States to collect information about people who were killed in motor vehicle crashes in the United States. FARS collects information on how the vehicle was involved in the crash—car, truck, or bus—and the age of the people killed. In 2005, 4,888 people ages 6-24 were killed in motor vehicle traffic crashes in the United States, accounting for 14 percent of the total 33,808 fatalities. The average age of the person killed was 41 years. About 24 percent were pedestrians, in contrast to 2 percent of those who were ages 80 and above. NHTSA estimates that approximately 20 percent of all deaths on rural highways involve teens and children riding with teen drivers. For example, following program prints 2, ‘hello’, True, True, False, 5, 3 and so on. Here, “_” means that parameter is not used in that call of a function.<n><n><n><n>def mymethod(*args, **keyword_args):<n>#This is main function<n>    print('my_function_name:',mymethod.__name__)<n>    #arguments passed inside method<n>    for arg in args:<n>        print(' ',arg)<n>    #keyword_ arguments passed inside method<n>    if keyword_args.size() > 0:<n>        for kwarg,value in keyword_args.items():<n>            print(' ',kwarg,': ',value)<n>print('Example input: ',)<n>mymethod(1,True,5,4)<n>mymethod('hi',False,3,True)<n><n>    if keyword_arguments.size() > 1:<n>        for kw_arg,arg_value in keyword_arguments.items():<n>     #print(arg_value)  <n>            print(kw_arg,arg_values)<n><n><n>### Output:<n>[1, 'hi', False, True, 3, True]<n>[2, True, False, True, False, False, 4]<n><n><n><n><n>### Your code should be working after making this modification<n><n><n>### Answer Key:<n>You should be able to obtain 140 points.<n><n>There is 1 wrong answer:<n><n><n>### Check your answer.<n>Use the input/output format when asking for help or getting additional clarification<n>

How many students play soccer?<n>Output: 45<n><n><hr /><n><n># Question 5 - Input & Output<n><n><hr />  <n><n>## Input and output example solution<n><n>###### Example Question 1<n><n>Input: Jan has 8 apples in her bag, while Aaron has 7 apples. Which has more apples?<n>Output: Jan<n><n>###### Example Solution<n>```<n>function countApples(input) {<n>    let Jan= Number(input[0])<n>    let Aaron= Number(input[1])<n>    if (Aaron>Jan) {<n>        return Aaron<n>    }<n>}<n><n>input = [Jan, Aaron];<n>```<n><n>###### Example Output Example<n><n>**Input: Jan has 15 apples in her bag**<n><n>```<n>countApples [ Jan has 15, Aaron has 20 ]<n>```<n><n>##### Example Output<n><n>**Output: 20**<n><n></hr><n><n>## Instructions<n><n>#### Input Example<n><n><hr /> <br /><n><n><n>Input:Jim went to the grocery while he was babysitting his baby daughter, Annie. He bought 5 potatoes and 3 apples. He spent a total of $23.10.<n><n>If the apples are $1.40 an apple, and the potatoes are $1.79 a potato, who was cheaper?<n>```<n>function getMoreCheap(input)<n>{<n>    let a= Number(input[2])<n>    let b= Number(input[3])<n>    let c= Number(input[4]-b)<n><n>    if (c>=b) {<n>        return a-c;<n>    }<n>}```<n><n></hr

Choices:  A: supermarket B: water C: cellars D: soup E: grocery store<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input: A box weighs almost 1800 grams. What does it weigh in kg? Choices: 1 A: Almost 1800 B: Almost 1701 C: almost 1700 D: approximately 1600 E: almost 1600<n>Output: A<n><n>Input: What is 23 subtracted from 12? Choices: 2 B: 12 C: 8 D: 13 E: 10<n>Output: D<n><n>Input: What division does 48/12 =? Choices: A B: 4 C: 6 D: approximately 6<n>Output: C<n><n>Input: Which number is the product of the following math operators in a short division problem? A 4 ÷ B 3 ____________? Choices: 7 3 = 7 = 4 A: 4 B: 12 Divide 12 by 4 C: 4 x 4 = 16 4 x 1 = 4<n>Output: C<n># Importing packages<n>import math<n># This function will return all prime factors of a number<n>def prime_factors(num):<n>    factors = [num]<n><n>    while(1 == True):<n>        if (num == 1) #Base case<n>            return factors<n>        elif (num % int(factors[-1])) == 0: # If the current number that we're considering is divisible by any of the previous ones we return this prime<n>            factors.pop(-1)<n>        if (factors[-1] == 2) # Base case<n>            return factors # If a prime that occurs less then two we must continue with the next number<n>        else:<n>            num = num//factors[-1]<n>            factors.append(num)<n><n>    return factors<n><n>def is_prime(num):<n>    if (num == 2):<n>        return True<n>    if (num % 2 == 1):<n>        return True # Odd numbers are always prime<n>    if (num%num == 0):<n>        return False<n>    for (i in range(3, num)): #Checks that for every odd prime i<n>        if (num%i == 0):<n>            return False

However, we should take into account that the numbers should be positive so<n>Brenda should have 52 cards whereas Mara should have 47 cards.<n><n>If Janets has 13 times more cards, then Brenda should have 3 times more cards than <n>Brenda whereas Mara should have more half of Janets.<n><n>

Choices:  A: tropics B: nightmare C: wyoming D: bushes E: feild<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Solutions:<n><n>### Q1) Answer<n>1. Janet has 9cards more than Brenda and mara 2x more than Janett. If Janett has 9 cards then mara has 2*19 (more than brenda) ie 38 - she has less than 151 and hence greater than 150.<n><n>Janett has 150 - mara has 38 - that ie 112 - brenda has 112 - 19 ie 93 then Janetta has 150 hence her cards will be 150-19-112-93= 211<n>### Q2) Answer<n>3. 5 is the first step in the chain 20 - he comes back(ie he doesn't go to the post office) that means 50.<n><n>### Q3) Answer<n>5. 10 blue chains - 3 times as much ie 30 - 13 less ie 17 - addie up we get 67<n><n>### Q4) Answer<n>7. 3 thermos - how many are there in anther - if u add them then 6 - answer<n><n>### Q5) Answer<n>9. 1/5 times as much ie 1.5 - so subtract that from 30 and we get 28. If we add 28+28+28=84 then 4*84 ie 336. Add 104 ie 430.<n><n>## Solution Q5

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:What does sex often make happen in people? Choices:  A: making love B: feel good C: happyness D: wonderful thing E: cloud judgment<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:The sum of 2, 4, 6, and 8 is the same as the sum of 300, 200, 480, 940, and 365. What is the sum of the 4 terms?<n>Output: 870<n><n>Input:Fred made 5 cookies. He gave 4 cookies to his friends and 1 cookie to his mom. How many cookies remained?<n>Output: 0<n><n>Input:What is an abbreviation for the letter N. Choices:  A) N. B) N. C)N. D) N. E) N.<n>Output: N.<n><n>Input:What fruit has three letters in its name? Choices:  E.g, Apple.F: Banana.<n>Output: Banana<n><n>Input:A cow, a chicken, and a horse are out for a walk. The cow says,"Hey, it's hot!" Why is it not the cow who is sweating?<n>Output: Because the cow is not the one who is sweating?

How many customers were there more than half of the people who came to the dinner? Choices: A) 40 B) 50 C) 35 D) 25 E) 65<n>Output: 65<n><n>Input: A man is in a house with three stairs. What is the total number of steps the man walks?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: The total number of apples that 5 boys and 3 girls bought was 207. They bought 11 apples more for the boys than the girls. How many apples did each get?<n>Output: 49.5<n><n>Input: What is 4.5 times 5?<n>Output: 7.5<n><n>### Explanation:<n>1. First, I use 2 for loop to loop through all of the 9 cards<n><n>```<n>    for(i=0;i<n;i++){<n>    card=9*i-8+3;<n>    sum=sum+1;<n>    }<n>```<n><n>The answer is 211.<n>2. Use multiplication for loop to increase the count.<n><n>```<n>    count++;<n>    num_count=num_count+1;<n>    ```<n>The output is 50.<n>3. Use a for-each loop to find blue, green and white.<n><n>```<n>   green_count=green_count + blue_count + white_count;<n>   white_count=white_count + green_count + blue_ount;<n>   blue_count=blue_count + white_ount;<n>```<n>The output is 67.<n>4. A for loop to loop through the sum and subtract the result to 1/5 of sum. To make it faster, I set another variable called sum1 to hold the current sum.<n>```<n>    temp=(sum-sum1)/5;<n>```<n>The answer is 6.<n>5. Use a for

How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:They checked the weather one more time during the flight, they were on their way to paradise and wanted it to what? Choices:  A: look beautiful B: be happy C: change quickly D: occur here E: surprise us<n>Output:		B<n><n>Important Notes for This Question:<n><n>The total number of cards in the deck of cards = 2 decks x 2 packs of cards (i.e. 4 packs in total) = 8 packs<n><n>2 cards - Brenda, 4 - Janet, 8 - Mara <n><n>If cards with Mara are 40 cards lesser than 150 then Mara is missing 110 cards (150-40 = 110)<n><n>Given 9 more than Brenda so Brenda has 2 cards more (Janet & Mara) <n><n>Sylvia also has 4 cards less than Brenda (2 cards each) so Sylvia's cards are 2 cards lesser than the remaining of the cards with Brenda and Janet. (10 cards more with Mara)<n><n>So in total 11 cards are missing with the two girls. (2 each cards from Brenda, Janet and Mara)<n><n>The total no. of cards left in the deck = 75<n><n>So with these remaining cards and Sylvia can distribute them equally each of them so each has 7 cards (i.e 23 each with Mara, Brenda & Janet) or can distribute it to the other as they like.<n><n>Output = 211 (Janet & Marra got 23 each)<n><n>Input: In the classroom there are 2 blue chairs, 3 green chairs and 1 white chair. All blue + all green + all white are 35 chairs. Number of white chair is 3 less than number of blue chair. It can be called like this:<n>def calculate_age(birth_year):<n>    """<n>    :type birth_year: str<n>    :rtype: int<n>    """<n>    today = datetime.datetime.today().year  # 2022<n>    current_age = today - birth_year<n>    if current_age < 0:<n>        current_age = -current_age<n>    return current_age<n><n><n># The next script tests calculating an age.<n><n># Test it here:<n>#input age<n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    age = 20<n>    result = calculate_age(age)<n>    print("age: %s" % age)<n>    print("result: %s" % result)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. Choices:  A: nature B: toilet C: computer science D: computer store E: human body<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:There are 8 apples in a basket which cost $0.75 per apple. If there are 2 apples fewer, how much less would be the cost of the apples in the basket?<n>Output: $0.37<n><n><n><n>#### Solution:<n>In order to solve multiple Choice based problem, we go for brute force solution, if the problem has less number of question, we could solve with recursive solution.<n><n>###### 9 cards more than Janet means Janet holds 9 cards and Brenda holds one less than Janet.<n><n>###### First, we find how much Mara has cards<n><n>mara has 150 - 40 = 110,<n><n>###### Now, we find Janet<n><n>Janet has 9 cards + 110=209 cards,<n>And<n>Brenda holds 150 -110 = 40 cards.<n><n>###### We do similar thing in 2nd block of question, find how much Pete has traveled<n>We know,<n>Traveling 40 blocks is traveling 4 times,<n>Pete walked 5 blocks + traveling 40 blocks,<n>5*4 = 20 blocks<n>And<n>He travelled 5 blocks from home to Bus Garage,<n>Pete walked back home,<n>Travel of home + Bus Garage --> 5+5=10<n><n>Total travel = 5+10 = 15 blocks<n><n>###### 3 times as many,<n>Givene example, say we have 2 blue chairs, 2 green chairs and 2 white chairs,<n>If we say, green chairs are  three times more than blue chairs.<n>We simply know, total number of chairs = blue + green + white,<n><n>we want to find, how many green chairs are there,<n>So, green chairs are three times,<n>So, it becomes<n>total green chairs = blue chairs * (3/2)<n><n>total green chairs is three times as many which is 9.<n><n>total chairs = (4 + 9 + 2) = 15<n><n>And for 2nd question<n><n>13 green and 3 blue means total of 16 green - 1 = 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:After new coke was discontinued what formula was used? Choices:  A: original B: old C: coke clear D: former E: familiar<n>Output:		D<n><n># Solution:<n><n>    class Solution:<n>        <n>        def minCoins(self, coins, target):<n>            '''<n>            :type coins: List[str]<n>            :type target: int<n>            :rtype: Set[int]<n>            '''<n>            <n>            dp = []<n>            for coinType in coins:<n>                dp.append([0] * target)<n>                dp[0][target - 1] = 1<n>            <n>            for i in range(2, len(coins)):<n>                last = i - 1<n>                subSet = dp[i]<n>                leftSet = dp[last]<n>                <n>                for j in range(last, i + 1):<n>                    currentSet = leftSet<n>                    setAdd = rightSet<n>                    sum = j + leftSet[-1] + 1<n>                    for x in range(1, sum):<n>                        leftSet.append(currentSet[-1])<n>                        currentSet = merge(leftSet, setAdd)<n>                        <n>                    subSet[-1] = leftSet[-1]<n>                    leftSet.pop(-1)<n>                    while j < i:<n>                        subSet.append(leftSet[0])<n>                        leftSet[0] = 0<n>                        j += 1<n>                            <n>                dp.extend(subSet)<n>            return dp<n>           <n>            '''<n>            Helper Functions:<n>            '''<n>             def merge(set1, set2):<n>                l =[]<n>                r = []<n>            <n>                for i in set1:<n>                    l.append(i)<n>                for j in set2:<n>                    r.append(j)<n>                    <n>                for i in range(len(l)):<n>                    if l[i] <= r[-1]:<n>                        l[-1] += r[-1]<n>                        r.pop(-1) <n>                return l <n>                <n>        <n>        def _helper(self, list):<n>            if(len(list) == 0):<n>                return set([])<n>            <n>            if(len==2):<n>                return self._helper(list[0]) <n>            else:<n>                newList = self._helper

If we can help with your code or approach, please feel free to post a reply.  <n><n>#### Letter Combinations of a Phone Number<n><n>---<n><n>##### Instructions:<n><n>Write a function that will take a phone number and an array of letters as parameters. The array consists of the letters A, B, C, and so on. The function should return all letter combinations that can be combined with letters from the call-in number to construct a word. For example, the letter combination "CAB" is the correct solution for a phone number of 225555237 (which has the letters: C A B E R). There should be a list of 13,340 possible letter combinations for this phone number. Below is the Python code for a solution. <n><n><n>```python<n>#!/usr/bin/env python<n><n><n>def find_combinations (phone_number, alphabet):<n>  # Phone number has 10 digits.<n>  # Each letter has a number between 1 to 9.<n>  # There are 8 letters in alphabet A-Z.<n>  # So, total number of letters in alphabet should be equal to: 11*11*8= 6,088 combinations.<n>  n = len (phone_number)<n>  combs  = len (alphabet) * len (alphabet)<n>  <n>  return combs<n>```<n><n><n>### Input: Enter a phone number, e.g.: 2255,5237<n><n><n><n>### Output: The phone number: 2255 5237<n>### Output: 13340 solutions<n><n>### Output Validation: Valid and expected solution.  No problems with your code or inputs<n><n><n>### Hint 1: Please see the question comments.<n><n><n>### Solution: Please post your solution in the next step.<n><n><n>## Step 2: Please post your partial code, if any.<n><n>## Step 3: If you are stuck, please post.<n><n>## Step: Once your problem/code is accepted please add step to

This phrase indicates in order to obtain a value that you can multiply with multiple values, you divide the total value to obtain each value individually. Choices:  A: chess set B: strategy C: toy store D: chess game E: small case<n>Output:		B<n><n>#### Solution:<n><n>#### Question 1:<n><n>- 134:  If we take Janet 9 and Brenda 13 then total = 22. <n>- 303 = Janet 9, Brenda 13 + Mara 3 = 36<n><n>#### Question 2:<n><n>- 400:  After travelling 5 blocks from his home to the bus garage, Pete traveled 20 blocks to get some stamps at the post office. Later, he traveled 5 blocks back, making a total distance of 10 blocks<n><n>#### Question 3:<n><n>10*3=30:  If we see the difference, then<n><n>Blue = 10, Green = 30, White = 4<n>We can substitute the values, Now we will obtain,<n>13+9= 22<n>30+10,10  = 40<n>40+13+9 = 52 (Total)<n><n>We can choose the 4th answer<n><n>#### Question 4:<n><n>30*31/18 = 841/36: We will convert them to fraction <n>8/2.5 = 6: She drinks 2 pints of coffee<n><n>#### Question 5:<n><n>30,80,50,30*31 = 140:<n><n>Since they each have 5 birds - 5 birds per day<n><n>140(5)*4 = 7*4 = 28!<n><n>#### Question 6:<n><n>18*2.25 = 40: 9*5*3+9 *5*3*1 = 45<n>45*50 = 2250: 45 = 225*20<n>7*3 = 21:<n><n>#### Question7:<n><n>18<n><n>####Question 8:<n><n>2<n><n>Explanation: 234-17= 117= 3*39+ 3=B<n>333-25= 308= 5*62+4/2= E<n>229-48= 1

So total number of chairs are 200+30=230<n>- There are 4.5 gallones of coffee in all<n>Alannah is 20 more so it means that in 4.5 gallones there is 20-20=0 and from this value no of thermos of beatrix =4.5-3<n>so total =4+3=7<n>- If we sum up 30 in Alannah's and 15 in brenda's, then total in all is 45 now we have to find number of berries in each birds i.e no of days so if 45 is divided by no fo birds (5), then no of berries in each bird is 9<n>- On the basis of this statement we can say that she take home all the sale items from mall i.e 18 clothes and in this statement sale items are free so there wud be no charge for anything.<n>- Secular parties are frequent in nature and not held on specific time and date

Choices:  A: detroit B: australia C: michigan park D: cafe E: retail store<n>Output:		Michigan park<n><n>Input:What is 1 times 1.5 times 2.5?<n>Output: 3.75<n><n>Input:1264343443603040221<n>Output: 3<n>```<n>### Code Solutions<n>We solved the first problem by using the modulo operator, and subtracted 150 from all of the total of the cards.<n>We used a `FOR LOOP` to travel 5 blocks from his home, to the bus garage.<n>We used a nested `IF` statement to find the total number of chairs.<n>We used an `IF` statement to compare a variable to a fixed value of `6` and set it to `6` if it equals or is greater than the variable.<n>We used a for loop to run iteratively which gave us the total amount to all of the variables.<n>```<n>i = 0<n>while i < 7<n>  i = i + 1<n>  j = i - 1<n>  if i = j<n>  print("This is a nested IF and the statement is true.<n>```<n>We used a nested While Loop to travel from Blacks, Martha, to Green Coffie (3 blocks travel) to Coney Island (5 blocks away from Green Coffie)<n>We solved the last problem by using a `FOR LOOP`.<n>Inside the loop <n>If i < 2 then multiply the number by 1 otherwise multiply the number by 2.<n>If i< 2 is false then skip.<n>If i<3 then multiply the number by.5 and add 1 to the value<n>Output: 31<n>```<n>### Explanation<n>This code below is a modulo operator, and is to be used in the `if` statement.<n>The output of the modulo operator will give the remainder which in this case is 150. Then subtract the 150 from the total of the cards, which is 211, then in your answer you would put the modulo of your result. Thus 211 mod. (150) or 41 would give you your final answer. This is useful in the scenario because you can put your variables next to each other and it will find your solution quickly without making a mistake which is better for speed at least.<n>```<n>

Choices:  A: empathy B: anxiety C: knowlege D: falling down E: hear things<n>Output:		knowledge<n><n>```<n># Python code:<n><n>def solution(a, b, c, d):<n>  if a!= b: #if a!= b<n>    x= a<n>    y= b<n>    x= d<n>    y= d<n>    i= y**2 - (-x + y)<n>  else:<n>    a= c<n>    b= c<n>    if a== b:<n>      while i> 0: <n>          i = i - 1<n>          a= d<n>          b= c<n>  return a**2 + b**2<n><n>if __name__=="__main__":<n>  with open("..\\.txt") as f:<n>    data = f.readlines()<n>    for d in data:<n>        data = d.decode("utf-8")<n>        a = int(data.split(None, 1)[0])<n>        b = int(data.replace("*", "").split(None, 2)[0])<n>        c = int(data.strip("Input").replace("Output", "").split(r"\s*$", 2)[0])        <n>        d = int(data.repalce("Input", "").replace("Output","").strip("*"))<n>        i= solution(a, b, c,d)<n>        print(f"{i} is the solution")<n><n>```

They push for 12 minutes and then their parents tell them to stop. How far did they travel in miles if it takes 1 minute and 12 seconds to travel 63/4 miles?<n>Output: 75<n>```<n><n>* Solution 1:<n><n>```python<n>import sys,os<n>from collections import Counter<n>from math import pow,factorial<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def sum_digits(self, n: int) -> str:<n>        """<n>        Given an integer n, return the sum of its digits.  <n>        For example, return "1" if n = 1, return "100" if n = 99.<n>        If n contains no digits, return an empty string.<n>        The sum of the digits of 1000 is 1000.<n>        Example 1:<n>        Input: n = 1000<n>        Output: "1000"<n>        Example 2:<n>        Input:<n>        n = 3900<n>        Output = "2998"<n>        Avoiding duplicate output in different test cases.<n>        Note that 1000 can output to "1000", the empty string "0", or "1".<n>        So the output cannot be the same string twice in different test cases. <n>        """<n>        count = Counter(str(n))<n>        unique_list = list(count.elements())<n>        <n>        count_str = ''<n>        for unique_value in unique_list:<n>            if unique_value!= 0:<n>                count_str += f'{unique_value}'<n>        return count_str<n>        <n>    def reverse_digits(self):<n>        pass<n>        <n>    def sum_even_digits(self) -> None:<n>        pass<n>

Instruction: A card is one of the 13 cards dealt to a player in a game of bridge. What is the 3-digit number of 2x plus the 3-digit sum of the numbers to the left and right of it? <n>##### Solution: <n>![](https://res.cloudinary.com/d35y26852/image/upload/c_scale,w_320/v1498197464/BridgeGame_y1n0kz.png)<n>##### Explanation:<n><n>24 + 11 (Sum of numbers to the left and Right of 7).<n>2 (7) + 4 = 9 (Sum =14)<n>Bridge Game Number =9+7=16  <n>Which is 18 in Roman Numerals.<n><n>#### 2. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:In the middle of the day what will someone do because of being hungry? Choices:  A: cook dinner B: make bread C: eat in restaurant D: have lunch E: make bread<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: The baker has 7 pieces of bread so far. Every morning he bakes bread so that the total does not go below 40 pieces of bread. How many days a week does he bake bread each day?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: Pumpkin, squash, and banana. These fruits are all round. They all have seeds. They all have many colors. But pumpkin is orange, squash is orange and green, and banana is yellow. All are great fruits. Which is NOT a round fruit?<n>Output: Squash<n><n>Input: 6 fruits were at the market. Each had 5 seeds. The total of seeds for 5 different fruits is 30. How many seeds did each fruit have?<n>Output: 4<n><n>### Explanation:<n><n>- Janet has 9 more cards than Brenda -> Janet has 150 - 9 + 9 + 9 - 9 = 211 <n>- 20 blocks by the bus to the post office -> 50 + 50 = 100<n>- 13 fewer white chair than green and blue chairs together  -> 3 * 13 = 39<n>- Genevieve drank as many pints of coffee the day she drank 3 thermos. -> 6 * 3 = 18<n>- Beatrix has 10 more books than Alannha.  Beatrix doesn't have as many books as Queen ->  160 + 10 - 30 = 130<n>- Alannah and Queen each ate 2 less berries than Samuel's birds -> 2 (Alannah's birds) * 2 (Queen's birds) - 5 (Sam's birds) = 6 berries<n>- Martha bought 2 jackets and 8 t-shirts -> 8 (t-shirts) + 8 ( jackets) <n><n><n>### Credits<n>1. https://github.com/peterfleetham/HSA_Chapter_18

If she has more cards than Brend, let the cards that she has more be m and the cards Brenda has more be n, therefore, the sum of cards would be<n>$$m-n$$<n><n>Secondly, we find the total number of cards in all of them by adding together the number of cards Janet has and subtracting the number that Brenda has which is 40.<n><n>$$m-n + 150 \Rightarrow 59-49 + 150 = 211$$<n><n>Output:<n><n>#### Explanatin:<n><n>We can use the substraction method to solve this<n><n>Firstly, add the distance that Pete walks from his house to the garage. Choices:  A: jail B: internet cafe C: blacksmith's shop D: building E: bar<n>Output:		Building / jail<n><n>#include <bits/stdc++.h><n><n>using namespace std;<n>int main(){<n>	int choice,n,m,b,f;<n>	char ch[2];<n>	scanf("%d",&choice);//input<n>	while(choice!= 'E'){<n>		switch (choice){<n>			case 'A':<n>				scanf("%d%d%d%d  ",&n,&m,&b,&f);//input<n>				if(m+b>n+f){<n>					printf("building");	<n>				}<n>				else{<n>				printf("%c",ch[0]);<n>				ch[2]='\0';<n>				b=n+f;<n>				m=n+b-n-f+n;<n>			}<n><n>			case 2:'<n>				int temp;<n>			scanf(" %d",&temp);<n>			<n>			if(temp==1){<n>	<n>			printf("jail");<n>				break;<n>			<n><n>			}else if(temp==2){<n>	<n>	<n>		<n>		if(temp!=2){<n>			printf("%d",b);<n>	<n>		}<n>	<n>		else{<n><n>		<n>	<n>	<n><n>	<n>	printf("bar");<n>		break;<n><n><n><n>	<n>	}<n>		}else if (temp==3){<n>		<n>	printf("%s", ch);<n><n>	}else{<n>		printf("internetcafe");<n>	}<n>	b=n+b-m+n;<n><n>	}<n>	}<n>}<n>

Choices:  A: study philosophy B: become adult C: ask questions D: further education E: study together<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:In some countries, the number of babies born to a woman is 3 on average.<n>What is the average number of babies in a family?<n>Output: 4<n><n>#Your answer here.<n><n>## Solution:<n><n>### Solution 1:<n><n>```py<n>answer = 0<n><n>for i, v in enumerate(input_list[::-1]):<n>    for j in range(5):<n>        if i+j == 1:<n>            answer += int(input_list[i+1][j])-1<n>    if v == "X":<n>        answer = 80-answer<n>        <n>answer += 9<n>```<n><n>### Solution2<n><n>```py<n><n>import math<n>import os<n><n><n>def find_sum(n):<n>    '''<n>    returns the sum of the integer list given<n>    input: a list of integers<n>    output: an integer<n>    '''<n><n>    total = 0<n><n>    for i in n:<n>        total+=i<n><n>    return total<n><n>def calculate_sum(x,y,c=23):<n>    '''<n>        takes an integer and returns the sum of it with a multiplier<n>        :param x: the integer to be added to<n>        :param y: the multiplier<n>        :return z:  the integer with multiplication<n>    '''<n><n><n>    if x >= c:<n>        return(x + (y-1) * 23)<n>    else:<n>        return(int(input(x-1)  * y))<n><n>        <n><n>    '''<n>    The code should be run without modifying to get the correct answer<n>    '''<n><n>from math import factorial<n>def factorial( x ):<n>    ''' returns the factorial of the current number<n>    input: the number<n>    output: factorial of number<n>    '''<n>    if  x==0:<n>        return 1<n>    else:<n>    return x * factorial( x - 1 )<n> <n>    return factorial(x - 1)<n>    <n>print(  factorial(15) )<n><n>```<n><n><n>#### Explanations:<n><n><n>#Explnation:In the first approach, the first line calculates the total number of books, then multiply their

"))<n>y = x * 0.25<n>if 1.25!= 12.5:<n>  output = (x + y)/2<n>else:<n>  output = math.ceil((x + y)/2)<n>print(output)<n><n>#Explanation:<n><n># Instruction:<n><n># x stands for Janet's card.<n># y stands for Brenda's card.<n><n># Janet has 9 more cards than brenda.<n># Mara has twice as much as Janet has.<n><n># How many cards altogether?<n># Since Janet has 9 extra cards, and mara has 40 less than 151,<n># (let's say x = 150)<n># <n># (x + 9) - 40<n># 150 - 40<n><n># In this example, Janet has 111 cards total.<n># Brenda has 106 cards.<n># They have a total of 211 cards together.<n><n>#Instructions:<n><n>#Distance between pete and his house: block<n>#Distance between pety and the buss: buss block<n>#Difference: pete buss minus pete hous minus buss <n><n>#How many blocks does pete travel: 50<n>#Block distance between petch's house and the buss: 5 +5= 10<n>#pete buss = 10<n>#Subtraction (10 -5 ) = 5<n>#Buss to pete's house= 5<n><n>#Instruction:<n><n>#Number of blue chairs: 10<n>#Green chair: 4 times more than blue = (104) <n>#White chair: 10 less than green = (80)<n><n>#Sum: 80 green and 100 blue<n><n>#Sum of: 67<n>#Output: 670<n><n>#Instruction 4:<n><n>#Number input to genevieve: 3<n>#Number output by genevieve:6<n>#Multiplication (6*(3)=18<n>#Output

Choices:  A: in books B: radio station C: city D: tower E: medieval castle<n>Output:		A<n><n>#### Answer:<n>```py<n>answer = 211<n>while len(line)!= 0:<n>    a = line[:]<n>    a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6 = map(int, a.split())<n>    answer = (6-a3)+answer<n>    print(answer)<n>    line = line.replace(','+',', '')<n>```<n><n>#### Solution:<n>```py<n>a,b,c,k = map(int, input().split())<n>answer = (a-b)+k<n>if not answer % 2:<n>    print(1+(answer//2))<n>else:<n>    print(answer/2)<n>```<n><n>#### Answer: <n>```py<n>answer=50<n>x=5<n>while x<=50:<n>    if x%2!= 0:<n>        pass<n>    else:<n>        answer+=x<n>    print(x,x%2)<n>    x+=1<n>```<n><n>#### Question: <n>```py answer=50 <n>while (len(line)!= 3 or not line.strip()):<n>    line=input().split()<n>    for i in line[1:]:<n>        if i % i == 0:<n>                answer+=i<n>        <n>        elif i % i == -1:<n>            answer-=i<n>        <n>        else:<n>            answer+=i<n>    if line[0] == "How many":<n>        for i in range(2,len(line)):<n>            if i % 2!= 0: <n>                break<n>            answer+=line[i]<n>print(answer)<n>```<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:What European country is famous for its potato industry? Choices:  A: idaho B: casserole C: new hampshire D: root cellar E: ireland<n>Output:		casserole<n><n>---<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```python<n>def solution(input):<n>  print(input) # print for debugging <n>  arr = input.split(',')[0].split(' ')<n>  answer = 0<n>  for i, num in enumerate(arr):<n>    n = int(num)<n>    if i > 0:<n>      if n >= 5: # at least 5 of total<n>        if (n % 6) == 0: # all multiple of 6<n>          if n % (6 * 5) == 0:<n>            if n/ 6 == 5:  # number of blocks per person<n>              answer += 325  # all even<n>        elif n % (6*5)!= 0: # at least 1 block<n>          pass<n>      else: # at least 2 of total<n>        arr[i-1] = (str(int(arr[i-1]) * 3.0) + str(int((arr[i-1] * 2.0) + 2500.0)))<n>        if (abs(int(n) % 6) == int(n / 6): <n>          if (abs(int((int(n)%6) * 2) ) % 1200 == 0): # how many blocks<n>            pass<n><n>  print(answer)<n>```<n><n>### Answer<n><n>```python<n>a1<n>Answer : 211<n>a2<n>Answer : 50<n>a3<n>Answer : 67<n>a4<n>Answer : 6<n>a5<n>Answer : 6.0<n>a6<n>Answer : 140<n>a7<n>Answer : 18.0<n>a8<n>Answer : B<n>```<n>

How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:Dave put his beer where he could get to it, but it would be off the floor.  Where did he put it? Choices:  A: zoo B: museum C: hospital D: desk E: opera<n>Output:		Zoo<n><n>Output: A<n>#### Solution<n><n>### Input: Janet has 8 cards more than Brenda<n>```<n>Janet = Janet + 8<n>Brenda = Brenda - 8<n><n>total = Janet + Brenda<n><n>```<n>### Input: Pete walked 4 blocks from his house to bus garage.<n>```<n>Total distance walked = walk to bus garage + walk from bus garage + walk to house<n>```<n><n>### Input; There are 10 chairs in all, and:<n>```<n>Blue chairs are 3 more than green chairs<n>13 chairs are white<n>No chairs are green.<n>```<n> <n><n>### Input<n>```java<n>4.5 gallons<n>= 4.5 * 0.01 * 1 = 4.5<n>= 0.5 * 4 * 20 + 4<n>```<n><n>## Solution<n>```java<n>Total = x + 5<n>Total + 1  = 15<n>```<n>```ruby<n>Total = x - 7 0.5 * Total = 8.5<n>```<n><n>## Reference<n>[Hackerrank](https://www.hackerrank.com/contests/winter-15/challenges/java-string-challenge/java-string-introduction)<n>[Python String Challenge](https://www.pythonserverside.com/python-string-solutions-hackerrank/)<n>

How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:The man needed flooring, where was he looking to install it? Choices:  A: loft B: home depot C: house D: tiles E: carpet store<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:The boy was eating his favorite cake, when it was interrupted by the girl, what was he eating? Choices:  a: donuts b: chocolate c: ice cream D: pizza<n>Output: A <n><n><n>## 🏆 Task 3(Part A)<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the given question.<n><n>## 𝐴, 𝐵, 𝐶<n><n>* 𝟐 is 𝟐0<n>* 𝘌𝘅 is 𝟑0<n>* 💡🎗 is 𝟒0<n><n>### Instructions:Input two values from the given list<n><n>## 𓃃 Counter<n><n>* 👒 is 0<n>* 𓊼 is 1<n>* 🔮 is 2<n><n>### Instuctions:<n>- Counter is incremented by one when the given conditions is a true.<n>- Counter is decremented by one when the value is false.<n>- Return to zero if the value is not given.<n><n>### Input:<n><n>- True<n>- False<n>- not defined<n><n>### Output:<n>- 2<n>- 1<n>- 𓃃<n><n>## 𒆜, 𒍟, 𒆨<n><n>* 𒆜 is 1𒍟<n>* 𒍟 is 1𒆨<n>* 𒅎 is 1𒷝<n>* 𒉪 is 1𒅞<n><n>### 💫, 💫<n><n>* 𓀑𓀑 is 10<n>* 𒃜𒃟 is 2<n><n>| **🗒 🗒 1** | **🗒** |<n><n>| **𝘗𝘢𝘵 is 𝘎 𝘥𝘢🗒  ** | **𝘗 is 𝘉 ������������  **
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:Mark wanted to know the truth, because he didn't want to continue existing in what? Choices:  A: understand B: were there C: ignorance D: in-between E: ignorant<n>Output:		C<n>What does in between refer to in the sentence and why?<n><n>A: I was at his house but I never saw him. I didn't want to ask him out. B: We were dating but I was having doubts. I'd never seen him with his parents. C: I was with him, but I didn't feel a thing I never felt that way before. D: I can't be in love with someone I never met before.<n><n>Instruction:Answer the following free text question.<n><n># Input<n>Mark wanted to know the _____, because he didn' think he could continue living in a world where ______.<n><n># Output<n>_____<n><n># Your Answer:<n>```python<n>def pig_egg(n, m):<n>    total_egg = 5<n>    total_pig = 1<n>    while n > 0 or m ==0:<n>        if n >= m:<n>            n -= m<n>            m = 0<n>            total_egg+=1<n>        else:<n>            n -= 1<n>            m += 1<n>            total_pig+=1<n>        print('How many eggs were left: {0:.2f}'.format(total_egg))<n>        print('How much pigs are: {0:.0f}'.format(m))<n>        print('')<n><n>    print('How many eggs left are {0:.03f}'.format(float(total_egg)))<n>    print('How much pig are left are  {0:.3f}'.format((float(total_pig))))<n>```<n><n>

He rode the bus to the post office. Later, he returned home the same way.How many blocks did Pete walk in all?<n>walked =int(input())<n>pete=0<n>while walked=walked:<n>    traveled = int(input())+walked<n>    walked=traveled - walked<n>    pete=pete+traveled<n>    print(pete)<n><n>```<n><n>```<n>pete=45<n>```<n><n><n><n>```python <n>#Input:Alannah, Beatrix, Queen are preparing for new school year and been given books by their parnets. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:Where can you see a mammoth in NYC? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: museum exhibit C: prehistoric times D: museum of natural history E: forest<n>Output:		D<n>*Hint: you need to think of how people see these things. For example, refrigerators are something people see in their houses/apartments.<n><n>Input: What is 8+9+8?<n><n>Output: 25<n><n>Input: How much did you spend on pizza?<n><n>Output: I ate it all!<n><n><n><n>## Solution <n>This is first task in solving the multiple choice questions in Rust which is a challenge in itself. In which I had to figure out on my own how to solve this question without any help. The process was very enjoyable but hard to learn how to solve, I can still not solve the next problem.<n><n>To start the program I had to create a struct for my "MultipleChoice" problem. To do that I used `use std::option::Some`and `Option,` to create a custom struct around an `Option`.<n>Next, the struct required a list of options and I created a `struct` named "Choice" which contained 4 different options to choose from, which would then be passed to the `struct` named "multipleChoice" that I created. These 4 different options contain a string type data for each one of them. Then, I needed to create an enum type that would correspond with each of the 4 options. (the name "choice" would have to be renamed to something in the future for the second part of the question which I'm going to explain in detail).<n>To start the program, I first created a type for the "string" data, which is going to be used in the enum type I created so I can compare values from the user input through the struct. Then, I created a struct with a single field that is a Vec of the enum type I created. That struct would take in an enum value and store is in the Vec, along with the user input through the question. Then, I created an array with all the choices from the struct that I named "choice" so I could compare the choices and the user input. Finally, I had the main function which would define the "chances" of getting the correct answer.  For example, if the user didn't give a correct answer they would have a 1/5 chance and if they were correct they will have a 4/5 chance if they had 4 choices.<n><n>These are the structures I created in my Program:
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. Add 10<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:8<n>Output: <n><n>Input: -16<n>Output: <n>-----<n>### Program to solve input by passing in variables<n><n>-----<n>**Solution**<n><n>If the user inputs an integer, the integer will be converted to a string and assigned to a variable. the program will then compare the variable value to the question. If the answer is correct, print the answer in the user readable format as shown in the sample code.<n><n>* For example if the user inputs -7, the string -7 will be converted to a variable and when compared to the question 'Subtract 9', if it is correct, the answer will be printed in a user friendly format i.e -6.<n>![output](images/out.png)<n>___<n>* If the answer is incorrect, the program will print no as correct answer and ask the user for another.<n><n>* Input = 4<n>* User variable = '4'<n>* Question = Subtract 8<n>* Output = 4 - 8 = -4<n><n>* Input = -4<n>* User variable  '4'<n>* No of loops (N) = 2<n>* Question = Substract 8<n>* Output -4 - 8 = 4<n><n>* Input -16<n>* User variable = -16<n>* Question = Subract 2<n>* Outpu = -16 - 2 = 2<n><n>* Input =-5<n>* User variable = '-5'<n>* Question =Subtrahct 9<n>* Output =-5 - 9 = ​34<n><n>* Input  =-10<n>* User variable =-10<n>

What rule does this work by and who do these children go with?<n>Output: Rule is: "7-1=6-1=5-1=4-1=3-1=2-1=1-1" i.e. when going from one to the next, the child left behind should be included. Therefore, children go together: one child will go alone with himself, the next child will go together with the other child, the next child with child, and so on till number of children remaining has only one, at which case one child must go with the next or else we will have paradox<n><n>Input: On Monday, I bought 12 apples. Choices:  A: ignore B: write C: learn new things D: illiterate E: having fun<n>Output:		A <n><n>### Explanation<n><n>**Explanation:**<n>```<n>#!/bin/bash<n><n>read -p "Please, enter number of cards?" first_number<n>read -p "How many cards Brenda has?" second_number<n>read -np "Please, enter number cards Mara has?" third_number<n><n>#We have 3 variable: first number, second number and third number<n>#Then, we'll use them in a few lines bellow<n><n>number_to_add=( $first_number $second_number )<n>total_cards=$(echo ${#number_to_add[@]} + 1)<n><n>#Here, we get the sum of the two variables<n>echo "Total of cards is $total_cards"<n><n>end_of_the_code=""<n><n>#At the end, we append end_of_the_codes to the array<n>echo "You have $total_cards cards in all"<n><n>#Example<n>#Enter number of cards: 85<n>#How many cards Brenda have? : 38<n>#How many cards has Mara have?: 287<n>#You have 369, 478 cards in all - correct answer<n><n>#Inputs: 91, 44, 262<n>#Output: Total of cards is 275, You have 275, 446 cards in all<n><n><n><n>### Exercise:<n><n>**Instruction:**<n><n>Your task is to develop a computer program to determine the number of stars in the sky.<n><n>**Input:** A computer program requests from the user to enter the desired number of stars, as a whole number smaller than 35,000.<n><n>**Output:** The computer program should display the number of stars the user entered using mathematical format, such as 123456789 - 012345.<n><n>**Example Input:** 6<n><n>**Example Output:** 6 stars.<n><n>**Example 2:**<n><n>**Input: 10,000**<n><n>**Example Output (formatted):** 10000 stars.<n>(The program should not allow you to enter numbers from 35,090, upwards)<n><n>

Each decimal point is for a dollar. <n><n>#### Solution<n>```javascript<n>const coins = {<n>    0.25: 800, <n>    0.5: 250, <n>    1: 100, <n>};<n><n>function giveCoins(coins, b, c) {<n>     c < 0? c = 0 : true;<n>     let t = b*100, r = 0;<n>     for(let v = t; v >= 0 && v < c;)<n>     {<n>          if(c/t - v > 0)<n>          {<n>               c -= (v / 100, Math.floor(v / 10));<n>               coins.v[0].v += (v % 100).toFixed(1)<n>               break;<n>          }<n>          else<n>          {<n>               t *= 10;<n>               c -= (c/t), v *= 100;<n>          }<n>     }<n>}<n><n>giveCoins(coins[1], 156.7, 8);<n>giveCoins.length<n>```<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>Write a function that determines a number’s position from a list of values. The function must return true if the value is in the list; otherwise false needs to be returned. The function will be passed the number that it should search for in the list. For example: If the number passed in is ‘3’, the function should return true if ‘3’ is found within the list of values and false if not.<n><n>#### Solution<n><n>```javascript<n>function check (arr, num) {<n>    for (var i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {<n>    if (arr[i] == num)<n>            return true;<n>    }<n>    return false;<n>}<n>```<n><n>## Requirment<n><n>### Instructon: <n>In this problem, two methods are needed:

Choices:  A: michigan B: lake C: tide pool D: nursery E: atlantic ocean<n>Output:		A <n> <n>## Solution:<n>The only way to arrive to the right answer is multiplying the choices without the last one.<n>### Solution 1<n><n>```python<n>    number1 = int(input())<n>    number2 = int(input())  <n>    number3 = int(input()) <n><n>    if number1>number2 and number2>number3<n>    number3 = number1-number2<n>    print(number3)<n>    return<n>    if number3>number1 and number1>number2<n>    number2 = number3-number1<n>    print(number2)<n>    return<n><n>    elif number3>=number2 and number3>=number1<n>    number1 = number3-number2<n>    if number1>=0<n>    print(number1)<n>    else<n>    print('infinity')<n>    return<n>    else<n>    return<n>        <n>```<n><n>### Solution 2<n><n>```python<n>while True:<n>    answer = intinput()<n>    if answer == 211:<n>        break  <n>    <n>while True:<n>   answer = intinput() <n>   if answer <= 40:<n>      break <n>   else:<n>       print("WRONG")<n><n>while True:<n>     answer = intinput()  <n>     if answer == 50:<n>         break<n><n><n>while True:       <n>    answer = int input()<n>    if answer < 10:<n>        break<n>      <n>    else:<n>        print("WRONG")   <n><n>while True:  <n>   answer = int input()  <n>    if answer <=5:<n>        break<n>     else: <n>        print("WRong!")  <n><n><n>while True :<n>    answer = (int input())  + (int input())  <n>    if answer < (755 + 20):  <n>        break <n>     else: 20 print("WRONG") <n>```<n>

How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input:You can buy a pen here. Choices:  A: briefcase B: pocket C: friend's house D: office supply store E: classroom<n>Output:		E (3,4,5,6)<n><n>Input:  The number of customers at a fast food restaurant is decreasing. In the morning, the number of customers increased by 100% from the previous hour, and it increased by 40% from the previous day. In the afternoon, the number of customers decreased by 100 from the prior hour, and it decreased by 40% of the prior day. In the evening, the number of customers went down by 200% from the prior hour, but it went up by 20% from the prior day. What is the final number of customers?<n>Output: 40<n><n>Input:"The car can travel 48 miles farther on a tank of gasoline than it can on one which is empty. The car traveled 360 miles this time and still had some left. How many miles does the car have left in its tank?"<n>Output: 86 miles.<n><n>### Source:https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/count-how-many-times-a-word-occurs-in-an-array/<n>---<n><n>### The idea:<n><n>---<n><n>The logic follows the same pattern as dynamic programming technique (https://learnupon.com/lessons/86891). Basically, we are going to generate all the possible combinations, use `reduce` (Python) or `apply` (R) to accumulate their summation and finally use `sum` function to count the sum.<n><n>---<n><n>## Solution<n><n>---<n><n>``````python<n>#!/usr/bin/env python<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n><n>from typing import List<n><n>def solution(words: List[str]):<n>    # type: (List[str]) -> int<n>    """<n>    Approach: Dynamic Programming <n>    Time: O(words.length), where the first 6 case is in O(1), and the following case is O((len(words) - len(picked-words)) ** 2), where len(picked-wors) = len(words) -1.<n>    Space: O(words.len() + 1)<n>    Complexity: O(words.lengt**2) <n>    """<n>    #

Choices:  A: make noise B: have tea C: make time D: make payments E: take time<n>Output:		C<n><n>---<n><n>You can use any programming language.<n>

If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket.
